description.plain:
Tame Impala is Kevin Parker’s psychedelic rock project from Perth, Australia. Originally signed to Modular Recordings, they are now also with Interscope Records.

The band came to prominence in 2010 with the release of their debut album, Innerspeaker. Their name refers to the impala, a medium-sized antelope. They see themselves as:

A steady flowing psychedelic groove rock band that emphasizes dream-like melody.

Here is another description, previously attributed to their website:

Tame Impala is the movement in the Orion Nebula and the slime from a snail journeying across a footpath. To humans, however, Tame Impala is more of a ‘music ensemble,’ but its various other forms should not be disregarded (colour that humans can see is only a small part of the electromagnetic spectrum, the rest is just as important to other things).

description.plain:
“The Less I Know the Better” describes the pain of a man feeling left out in a love triangle, illustrated with a complex arrangement of groovy bass hooks, sensual Rhodes piano chords, and moody synth textures.

Tame Impala frontman Kevin Parker has said that the song doesn’t belong on the album “because it has this dorky, white disco funk.” However, it is by far the most popular track on Currents, thanks in no small part to its breakout music video fusing psychedelia, sex appeal, high school angst, and a man in a gorilla costume.

This track follows the synth vignette “Gossip,” suggesting that the narrator, voiced by Parker, is hearing news about the woman he wants – that she is hooking up with someone named Trevor. The song’s title comes from his insecurity – if people give him the details of his crush’s sexual activity, the more it will dominate his thoughts and leave her seemingly defiled in his mind (“is this who you are?”).

As illustrated by the music video’s gorilla, Trevor vs. Kevin appears to be the classic “alpha-beta” struggle for women’s affections. Trevor has her attention for now because of his sexual prowess (he is her “lover… like every night”), but she knows that Parker would be the better long-term partner (“Wait ten years, we’ll be together”). However, Kevin warns her that his patience will not last “forever.”

Following its success on the record, “The Less I Know The Better” was released as a radio single on November 29th, 2015. The song was voted number 1 in Triple J’s Hottest 100 of the decade.

songs.title: New Person, Same Old Mistakes

description.plain:
On the final song of Currents, the narrator admits that his metamorphosis should be read with caution – its biggest skeptic is the side of him he left behind.

The impulse to change and the fear of changing too much are at odds until the bridge, which suggests some synthesis: “This story ain’t so different from the rest.” Change and self-doubt are natural, and in the end the narrator is the same introspective person he was on Innerspeaker and Lonerism.

It’s a fitting conclusion to an album that both describes personal transformation and embodies it musically, as a radical departure from Kevin Parker’s earlier work. Both fans and artist are forced to reconcile the past with the present, and the “realization” that one person can express different aspects of themself at different times “is as good as it gets.”

This song was covered by Rihanna on her album, ANTI, under the title “Same Ol' Mistakes.”

This song was also used in teasers for FX’s show created by Donald Glover, Atlanta. Glover is also known as the rapper Childish Gambino.

songs.title: Let It Happen

description.plain:
On the opening track of Tame Impala’s third record, Currents, Kevin Parker introduces the album’s theme of “letting go” and allowing nature to take its course, merging Tame Impala’s signature psychedelic rock sound with an extended electronic breakdown.

This theme is where the album derives its title, as Parker stated that the currents he refers to are “unstoppable forces” that lead to personal transformation.

“Let it Happen” was the first song revealed from the album, although it’s first official single was “‘Cause I’m a Man.”

description.plain:
On “Yes I’m Changing,” Kevin Parker sings straight from the heart about his very public break-up with Melody Prochet.

The lyrics are perhaps so stream-of-consciousness that he doesn’t remember writing them. According to an April 2015 NME article, it was:

…a  weird experience, because it was like it was someone else made the song. I had no memory of imagining it.

On this track, it starts to become clearer that this album is specifically about the loss of a lover and the end of an era, but also the beginning of something mysterious and new.

songs.title: Borderline

description.plain:
This is a “reworked” version of Tame Impala’s April 2019 single “Borderline,” which was also the first single released for The Slow Rush. Kevin first revealed that he had reworked the song in a December 18th, 2019 interview with BBC 1 Radio’s Annie Mac, stating:

However, as of February 14th, [2020]… as of that day, [the single] version will forever be known as the old “Borderline.”

Compared to the single version:


The background vocal at the beginning is removed
A different snare is used
The vocals are clearer, possibly from a stereo-shaper
A Moog Bass Synth is used, highlighting the bass
Before Verse 2, a laser synth and snares are added
During Verse 2, acoustic strings are added
The second line in Verse 2 is spoken faster
In Verse 2, ‘'asking how I managed’‘ is changed to ’‘I wonder how I managed’'
In Verse 2, ‘'get away’‘ is spoken differently
Before the first refrain, the volume is decreased and a short reversed sample is washed out with reverb, allowing the refrain to stand out more
Synths are added to the background of every fourth line in the second half of the first refrain
A background line is added at the end of Verse 3
Background vocals are added to the third chorus

songs.title: Borderline (Single Version)

description.plain:
On “Borderline,” the lead single from Tame Impala’s fourth studio album, Kevin Parker deals with themes of a relationship on its last legs while questioning the nature of love. The track was premiered on Saturday Night Live on March 30, 2019, and included slightly different lyrics. The full song leaked on April 11, 2019, the day before the official release.

“Borderline” was preceded by standalone single “Patience” which was released a little over a week earlier.

Parker appropriates “borderline,” most frequently employed as an adjective, as a noun. While immigration and borders continue to be prominent topics on a global scale, here he uses “borderline” as a personal metaphor for the rocky in-between spaces of a turbulent relationship. “Borderline” further carries, as an adjective, connotations of uncertainty and risk. People can be described, for example, as “borderline alcoholics,” a theme that crops up in the refrain (“Starting to sober up”). There is also “borderline personality disorder” (BPD), which the National Institute of Mental Health says often causes problems in relationships, which is itself the theme of the song.

description.plain:
“Eventually” is the fourth single released from Tame Impala’s third album, Currents, following “Let It Happen,” “Cause I’m a Man,” and “Disciples.” It dissects the impending end of a relationship and the difficulties in doing so, attempting to emphasize the latter part of the phrase “short term pain, long term gain.”

In a 2015 Reddit AMA, Kevin Parker pinpointed this song as the emotional core of Currents:

I have to say though, there’s a song on the new album called Eventually that is still very moving for me to listen to even after 951520974 listens and mixes.

Shortly after its release, Samm Culley from ‘60s/'70s funk band Skull Snaps accused Kevin Parker of sampling drums from their track “A New Day,” previously sampled by many hip-hop producers. Culley threatened to sue Parker, who responded by posting a photo of the email on Instagram with the caption:

WOW unexpected compliment! The creator of the famous Skull Snaps drum sample thinks my drums IS his actual sample and wants to sue me for not clearing it! Haha!! Sam Culley you have 3 days to fire your musicologist. Anyone think this could be a hoax though?

songs.full_title: Posthumous Forgiveness by Tame Impala
songs.title: Posthumous Forgiveness

description.plain:
“Posthumous Forgiveness” is the third single from Tame Impala’s fourth studio record, The Slow Rush. The song features Parker speaking on his deceased father, with whom Kevin had an estranged relationship due to his parents' early divorce. The first half of the track features a funk heavy bass line reminiscent of Innerspeaker, while the second half features a wall of synths similar to those on Currents.

On December 1st, 2019, a listing for the track appeared on streaming services with a release date set for December 3rd, 2019. It also revealed the track’s duration and its place in the record’s tracklist. On December 2nd, the track’s title appeared online. The track was previously teased by Parker on his Instagram on March 10th, 2019.

The first part of the song speaks about Kevin’s dislike for his father’s actions when he was still alive. He struggles to come to terms with the distance they shared from one another, “But you decided to take all your sorrys to the grave.”

The second part of the song welcomes a change of beat, and with it a change of heart. Kevin is reminiscing about the times he did have time with his father, and yearns to spend the time he missed with him, “Wanna tell you ‘bout my life, wanna play you all my songs.” He wants his father to be proud of him.

“Lost In Yesterday” is the fourth single from Tame Impala’s fourth studio album The Slow Rush. The song features Kevin singing about nostalgia, and letting things go from the past that can be haunting to people. He wants listeners to take bad memories and “lose them in yesterday,” leaving them behind by coming to terms with them.

The track was first announced by Kevin in a post featuring the single’s official artwork on the act’s official Instagram page on January 1, 2020. He also revealed that the track would come in the week following the post.

Before its official announcement, however, the track started appearing on streaming services as an unavailable track. This revealed that it would appear as the eighth track on the record.

songs.full_title: The Moment by Tame Impala
songs.title: The Moment

description.plain:
Much like album opener, “Let It Happen,” “The Moment” focuses on going with the flow and living mindfully, but with the added element of learning to be impulsive and make crucial decisions when the time is right.

On Currents, this track delivers a jolt of positivity after the trip-addled existential dread of “Nangs,” mirroring how one must continue onward despite periods of doubt.



Kevin Parker once said:

‘The Moment’ is the song that I most closely associate with the old Coogee Power Station. There are parts of the song that, when I listen to now, I’m right back there. The synth-guitar breakdown was directly inspired by standing at its base, looking up at it.

songs.full_title: Elephant by Tame Impala
songs.title: Elephant

description.plain:
Tame Impala’s first major hit was inspired by the arrogant bands and artists that Kevin Parker encountered in the Perth rock scene; who were certain of their future success. In August 2012, Parker told Stereogum:

‘Elephant’ is actually one of the oldest songs that I have, it’s just been in the vaults this whole time. I’m not sure why we never recorded it before, but we were just playing it at a sound check one night and everyone in the band was like, ‘We should just put this on the album,’ and so we did.

While Parker eventually admitted that he grew tired of the song, he hasn’t undersold its overall significance. As he told Grantland in June 2015:

[‘Elephant’] paid for half my house.

description.plain:
On “Breathe Deeper,” Kevin considers stressful and negative situations, how deep breathing can help with staying calm and making it through the situation.

The track was first teased in Q Magazine with the description:

An album track that sums up Kevin Parker’s approach on the brilliant new Tame Impala, fusing spacey synths, throbbing house pianos and shuffling beats with the frontman’s dreamy melodies.

On December 24th, 2019, news sources began reporting that the track would be released later that week as the fourth single from the record. However, it was not, and “Lost In Yesterday” ended up being the fourth single instead.

On Spotify, Kevin says this is the song most influenced by Mariah Carey, as well as The Neptunes and Pharrell. He also mentioned that he was also inspired by his first time on ecstasy.

songs.full_title: It Might Be Time by Tame Impala
songs.title: It Might Be Time

description.plain:
“It Might Be Time” is the second official single from Tame Impala’s fourth studio album, The Slow Rush. It leaked online on October 27, 2019, and officially released two days later. The lyrics concern the passage of time, how people change, and how this can affect a relationship. The title might be a reference to the time that has passed since Kevin Parker released his last album, Currents, in July 2015—now might be the time for his follow-up.

Parker described the song and the album’s release date in an October 2019 Instagram post:

I’ll be waiting anxiously with you until feb 14 2020, in the meantime enjoy this quirky new song about your own inner paranoid thoughts telling you you’ve lost your mojo, and whose drum sound took me about 1 of those 4 billion years. love you all

“It Might Be Time” appears to be inspired by ‘70s prog-rock acts like Supertramp, sharing similarities with their March 1979 hit, “The Logical Song.” Kevin has spoken in the past about his love for the group, listing Breakfast in America as one of his Top Five favorite albums.

songs.full_title: Patience by Tame Impala
songs.title: Patience

description.plain:
“Patience” is a single that was released in the interim between Tame Impala’s third album Currents and fourth album The Slow Rush. The title is perhaps a nod to the four-year wait for new music since the release of Currents  and its companion B-Sides & Remixes EP.

The disco-inspired track features Kevin singing over a bright piano groove and arpeggiated synths. The lyrics possess an intriguing ambiguity in that they could be musing both on Parker’s musical career and/or a relationship. Has it been that long since the last album? Since they started dating? People want to know what he’s doing after the tour, or maybe after a relationship ends. Either way, time weighs down on us all, as explored in the second verse, giving urgency to all relationships, whether with one’s art or one’s lover.

songs.title: Nangs

description.plain:
“Nangs” is a wobbly, disorienting track named after the Australian slang term for canisters filled with nitrous oxide (N2O), a compound gas used in cars to boost speed and transmission, or laughing gas. Nangs are occasionally used as a recreational drug; in the United States, they are known as whippets.

The song’s introduction sounds like a balloon filled with N2O being inhaled, which is the method used to get the gas into your system. The track does a good job of emulating the woozy, undulating feeling of being high on N2O.

“Reality In Motion” zooms in on the thought process of making the first moves with a new romantic or sexual interest, filled with copious amounts of self-doubt and hesitation.

Though Currents marks a major change in sound and mood for Tame Impala, this song most resembles those from the previous record, Lonerism, in particular the songs “Music to Walk Home By” and “Nothing That Has Happened So Far Has Been Anything We Could Control,” from self-doubting lyrics to a mid-lyric cutoff to wrap up the track, a signature of the band’s earlier work.

songs.full_title: On Track by Tame Impala
songs.title: On Track

description.plain:
“On Track” is an optimistic track featuring themes of perseverance and reaching one’s goals, which is an overall theme throughout The Slow Rush. The song is a downtempo moment on the tracklist, starting with piano and slowly building with layers of droning synths and drums.

In a February 2020 interview with Michéle Cuvelier of Studio Brussel, Kevin Parker described the song as “the emotional core of the album” and also said the song was inspired by the power ballads of artists like Supertramp and Meat Loaf.

description.plain:
“It Is Not Meant To Be” serves as the introduction to Tame Impala’s debut studio album Innerspeaker. It features a psychedelic rock instrumental that Kevin typically works in.

On the track, Kevin contrasts his life against a woman’s who he is interested, as the two have very different personality types. He lives a laid-back, relaxed lifestyle, while she likes a fast-paced lifestyle that is all business. The difference in lifestyles plays back into the track’s title, with Kevin acknowledging that all these differences are the doom of their relationship.

description.plain:
Being the sixth track in Tame Impala’s sophomore album, “Why Won’t They Talk to Me” is Kevin Parker’s realisation that he needs human connection.

After 2010’s “Solitude is Bliss” from their first full-length album Innerspeaker, Parker is finally realising that he starves for close connection and reciprocation in a relationship. As the first few lines establish, Kevin is not accepted by being himself and is tired of playing another person. This song is him questioning loneliness and himself in the world.

songs.full_title: One More Year by Tame Impala
songs.title: One More Year

description.plain:
“One More Year” kicks off The Slow Rush with a reverberating groove and vocal snippet that Kevin refers to as the “Gregorian Robot Choir.” The instrumental of the track is made up of Kevin saying the title of the song. On the track, Kevin talks all about the concept of time and not caring about its limiting factors, but rather living life to its fullest in spite of them.

The track first had its title and position in the track listing for The Slow Rush revealed by Kevin in his BBC 1 Radio interview with Annie Mac on December 18th, 2019. Annie, who had heard the track already, praised it as “beautiful and touching.”

songs.full_title: Tomorrow's Dust by Tame Impala
songs.title: Tomorrow’s Dust

description.plain:
On “Tomorrow’s Dust,” Kevin writes again on the theme of time, the most prominent motif of The Slow Rush. He points to the temporary nature of “yesterday” and how passing days immediately become the past, urging the listener to not focus on yesterday and forget it as the title of the track, “Tomorrow’s Dust.”

Previously, the track was thought to be titled “Wild Horses” due to a copyright strike on a fan-made mashup on January 4, 2019. The mashup included the song in the trailer for the project,  released October 24, 2019.

The woman on the phone at the end of the song is confirmed to be Kevin’s wife, Sophie Lawrence. Kevin speaks about this part in an February 2020 interview with triple J:

I wanted to get her talking on the phone, and so much of this album has to do with the future and what’s going to happen and the rest of your life, kind of thing. She spent some time in London and when she came home she was kinda like at a loss, where she felt like she didn’t know where she was going in life and the future was so uncertain.

songs.full_title: Solitude Is Bliss by Tame Impala
songs.title: Solitude Is Bliss

description.plain:
“Solitude Is Bliss” possesses perhaps the most accessible classic rock/pop sensibilities of Tame Impala’s first album Innerspeaker. The song makes heavy use of effects associated with 60s and 70s psychedelic, with Britpop-like instrumentation. Heavy panning effects contribute to the psych vibes, also reinforce visually through the album art by frequent Tame Impala collaborator Leif Podjhasky.

Thematically, the song’s perspective is that of an outsider observing his peers. Rather than socializing like them, and engaging in exterior relationships, he prefers solitude and relishes how his thoughts are unique to himself, never to be known by the “you” addressed in the chorus.

description.plain:
The first track on Tame Impala’s Currents B-Sides & Remixes picks up on the theme of recovering from love that’s explored on Currents. Here, Kevin Parker broods on the steps he’s taking to get over an ex-lover. At a certain point, you’ve got to get over someone and in Parker’s case add them to “a list of people to try to forget about.”  Not unlike, “The Less I know the Better”, he has to let go of waiting for a love that isn’t going to happen.

If you’re wondering why this track was left off Currents, Parker explained to Beats 1’s Zane Lowe that the song was made between Tame Impala’s albums Lonerism & Currents. He said:


I guess maybe one of the reasons it didn’t end up on the album Currents was that it was started on so early and I was so over it by the time I was finishing the album.

But by the time I got to finish the track, I was really kind of like satisfied with it as a song and as a chunk of my creativity and emotion and stuff.


Listen to his full Beats 1 interview here.

songs.full_title: Keep On Lying by Tame Impala
songs.title: Keep On Lying

description.plain:
“Keep On Lying” is the eighth track from Tame Impala’s Lonerism. Multiple songs from the album feature ambient sounds recorded by Parker on his dictaphone, which he explained:

I obsessively record sounds wherever I am. Like, if I’m at a train station, I’ll record the trains or a megaphone talking. I love ambient sounds. For me, it’s like taking photos. I love the idea of recording a collection or a library of weird sounds of stuff.

An example of this is on the track “Keep on Lying,” which features a recording of people talking at a party which has been digitally manipulated with delay added. In an interview with MTV, Parker said:

It’s meant to sound like there’s this dinner party going on and there’s music playing in the background and for me it makes the listener feel even more alienated.

songs.full_title: Why Won't You Make Up Your Mind? by Tame Impala
songs.title: Why Won’t You Make Up Your Mind?
songs.title_with_featured: Why Won't You Make Up Your Mind?

description.plain:
“Why Won’t You Make Up Your Mind?” was released as a single in 2011. It was recorded during the sessions for the Innerspeaker album in 2009, and released as the fourth single from that album, where it also appears as track 5. The single features artwork from Australian artist Leif Podhajsky, who also created the artwork for Innerspeaker and the follow-up Lonerism.

“Why Won’t You Make Up Your Mind?” was written by Kevin Parker in the key of F major in a 4/4 time signature. It is based around four repeating barre chords of A minor, B-flat major, E minor and F major, played on electric guitar, to create a trance-like, hypnotic and spacious atmosphere, while the bass is played rhythmically to fill in the guitar spaces.

It starts with three hi-hat hits on the drums, which was included by Parker as a tribute to the Outkast song “Hey Ya!” which starts with an uncommon three upbeats, rather than the more common four upbeats. Before the verse starts, a pitch-shifted, delayed, fuzz guitar kicks in, which many mistook for a synth, to play a melody in the F major scale, featuring stereo panning effects to give it a sense of movement.

The verse starts, featuring Parker’s vocals, which are reverbed and delayed. The lyrics are minimal and only featured in the verses, while a heavily chorused, distorted guitar plays a riff in the choruses.

Another verse comes in repeating the same lyrics, which gives way to a psychedelic outro, featuring many guitar overdubs with effects added to them coming to a crescendo. At only 3:19, “Why Won’t You Make Up Your Mind?” is the shortest track on Innerspeaker.

songs.title: Gossip

description.plain:
“Gossip” is Tame Impala’s Sixth single from Currents. It was recorded in March, 2012 but later published with the rest of the album tracks in Jul 17, 2015.

 Currents was preceded by the release of the singles “Let It Happen”, “Cause I’m a Man”, “Disciples” and “Eventually”. Like its predecessors, the album received critical acclaim, and it became the group’s best charting release. At the 2015 ARIA Music Awards, Currents was awarded Best Rock Album and Album of the Year, while at the Annual Grammy Awards, it was nominated for Best Alternative Music Album. Recording the album soon became an obsession to Parker, as he worked “all day, every day,” growing increasingly isolated.  Parker said:

At some point, life outside the studio fades into the distance. That’s how I know that I’m into it.

He reasoned that any alternate approach would imply that the music was not powerful enough.

songs.title: Be Above It

description.plain: “Be Above It” incorporates an interesting juxtaposition as the opening track to Lonerism. While the looping, fast-paced drums represent one’s eagerness for immediate success, the deliberate pacing of the vocal melodies suggest the reality that it won’t happen overnight. It is the rock star’s mantra to exercising patience.

songs.title: Runway, Houses, City, Clouds

description.plain:
Innerspeaker’s penultimate, “Runway, Houses, City, Clouds” is a whirlwind of heavy bass lines, foamy guitar riffs and psychedelic fuzz. By far the longest song from the album at seven minutes and 15 seconds long, Runway details the struggles of traveling, facing one’s ego, and escaping the past.

The title “Runway, Houses, City, Clouds” could represent the images Kevin sees as he travels.

songs.full_title: Sundown Syndrome by Tame Impala
songs.title: Sundown Syndrome

description.plain:
“Sundown Syndrome” was recorded in March 2009 and released later on in Jan 1, 2009. it is the 1st single in “Tame Impala’s EP; Sundown Syndrome/Remember Me- EP also available in iTune’s Innerpeaker Collectors Edition

Past “Tame Impala” releases were done by Kevin Parker purely for his own enjoyment. Innerspeaker marks the first time Parker has “recorded something for an intended release. In the past (he has) just recorded a song, then done another two weeks later and eventually put them together.” Recording started in June 2009 and finished in August 2009. Parts of the album were recorded all over the house, with some additional recording took place at Poon’s Head Studio and at Parker’s House. Regarding the recording environment, Parker said:

The idea of going to some flash studio where there’s some stranger telling you how to arrange your song is pretty absurd to us.

Consequently, the majority of the album was recorded and produced by Parker, with Jay Watson and Dominic Simper contributing small parts to the recording.

songs.full_title: The Boat I Row by Tame Impala
songs.title: The Boat I Row

description.plain:
Ethereal choral vocals and twinkling synths make this Slow Rush B-Side a track that wouldn’t feel out of place on Tame Impala’s previous album, Currents. Yet the crisp drum groove, more exploratory bass noodling, and Bee Gees-esque backing vocals help place this firmly in the Slow Rush era.

Lyrically, Kevin Parker confronts the themes that have become so endemic to his oeuvre, including feelings of self-doubt and the recognition that no one really knows what’s going on in this strange world we’re inhabiting. Nonetheless, he’s going to keep going, rowing down the river he’s been on since the Tame Impala project began.

songs.full_title: I Don't Really Mind by Tame Impala
songs.title: I Don’t Really Mind

description.plain:
The final track on Innerspeaker; “I Don’t Really Mind”, a track which has a driving drum beat supporting a rush of Lo-Fi, overdriven synths. The only recorded version of the song appears on the album. It includes a sickly, synth guitar tone, something that Kevin says he had an obsession with doing around the Innerspeaker.

Several months after the album’s release he was interviewed by Rollo & Grady in Los angeles in their known local Radio (KXLU 88.9 FM):


“R&G: What’s the meaning behind the album title, InnerSpeaker?”

“Kevin: It’s meant to suggest that the songs come from somewhere internal, rather than slowly taking shape with a bunch of guys jamming in a room. One way of writing a song is that you’ve got an idea in your head and build a song around that. Another is more of a collaborative thing: It starts out as nothing and gets put together with whatever happens. This album was very much a case of the former; it’s meant to give off the idea that the songs would be preserved.”

description.plain:
“Forty One Mosquitoes Flying In Formation” is the fourth single in Tame Impala’s EP album. It was later in 2010 sampled/remixed by “Poolside” and renamed “41 Mojitos (Canyons) Poolside Dub” on an album titled Extraspeaker, which also appears in iTune’s Innerspearker Collectors Edition.

The songs in EP were selected from a list of approximately 20 songs that Kevin Parker had recorded as far back as 2003, which he had sent to their label Modular Recordings. Speaking about the EP release Parker said:

Most of the songs on the EP were never meant to be heard by the rest of Perth, let alone the rest of the world. They were just recorded for my own listening sake, and burning a CD of it and putting it in my car and giving it to my friends.“ Parker also revealed that "The EP was not in anyway recorded for an EP. The songs that were on the EP weren’t even recorded at the same time, they were done over a bunch of years.
